  "prompt": "What is the use of microbeads in cosmetics?",
  "response": "Microbeads are tiny, solid plastic particles, typically less than 1 millimeter in diameter, that have been used in cosmetics and personal care products for several purposes. Their primary uses include:\n\n1. **Exfoliation**: Microbeads are commonly found in facial scrubs, body washes, and exfoliating products. They help remove dead skin cells and impurities by physically scrubbing the surface of the skin.\n\n2. **Texture and Sensory Experience**: In products like toothpaste, cleansers, and creams, microbeads can enhance the texture and provide a unique sensory experience.\n\n3. **Color and Visual Appeal**: Microbeads can add a decorative element to products like shampoos and shower gels, making them visually appealing.\n\n4. **Functional Roles**: In some cases, microbeads are used to deliver active ingredients or improve product consistency.\n\n### Environmental Concerns\nDespite their cosmetic benefits, microbeads have raised significant environmental concerns. Because they are made of non-biodegradable plastics (such as polyethylene or polypropylene), they can persist in the environment for hundreds of years. When washed down drains, they enter waterways and oceans, contributing to plastic pollution. Marine life often mistakes microbeads for food, leading to ingestion and potential harm to ecosystems.\n\n### Regulatory Actions\nIn response to these environmental impacts, many countries, including the US, Canada, the UK, and members of the European Union, have implemented bans or restrictions on the use of microbeads in cosmetics and personal care products. Manufacturers are increasingly turning to natural, biodegradable alternatives, such as salt, sugar, crushed nut shells, or jojoba beads, for exfoliation and other purposes.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
